1
00:00:01,140 --> 00:00:06,170
The price rate of change (ROC) represents
a momentum oscillator, measuring the speed

2
00:00:06,170 --> 00:00:10,520
at which the price is changing within a defined
time period.

3
00:00:10,520 --> 00:00:15,830
The rate of change (ROC) calculates the percentage
change between the most recent price and the

4
00:00:15,830 --> 00:00:19,199
price registered a certain number of periods
ago.

5
00:00:19,199 --> 00:00:24,279
The plot forms an oscillator moving above
and below the zero line as the rate of change

6
00:00:24,279 --> 00:00:26,099
moves from positive to negative.

7
00:00:26,099 --> 00:00:32,189
So the ROC indicator is plotted against zero,
with the indicator moving upwards into positive

8
00:00:32,189 --> 00:00:38,160
territory if price changes are to the upside,
and moving into negative territory if price

9
00:00:38,160 --> 00:00:41,890
changes are to the downside.

10
00:00:41,890 --> 00:00:48,620
Like other momentum indicators (Stochastic
oscillator, for example), ROC can be interpreted

11
00:00:48,620 --> 00:00:52,640
in numerous ways, traders using this oscillator
for overbought/oversold signals, divergences

12
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:54,309
and zero-line crossovers.

13
00:00:54,309 --> 00:01:04,250
A value above zero indicates an increase in
bullish momentum and a negative value suggests

14
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:06,439
an increase in downward momentum.

15
00:01:06,439 --> 00:01:11,200
A rising ROC typically confirms an uptrend.

16
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:16,660
But this can be misleading, as the indicator
is only comparing the current price to the

17
00:01:16,660 --> 00:01:18,200
price N periods ago.

18
00:01:18,200 --> 00:01:25,100
A falling ROC indicates the current price
is below the price N periods ago.

19
00:01:25,100 --> 00:01:31,070
This usually helps confirm a downtrend, but
isn't always accurate.

20
00:01:31,070 --> 00:01:35,380
When the price is consolidating, the ROC will
hover near zero.

21
00:01:35,380 --> 00:01:41,090
In this case, it is important traders watch
the overall price trend since the ROC will

22
00:01:41,090 --> 00:01:46,540
provide little insight except for confirming
the sideways movement.

23
00:01:46,540 --> 00:01:51,969
Overbought and oversold levels are not fixed
on the ROC, and each asset will generate its

24
00:01:51,969 --> 00:01:54,110
own extreme levels.

25
00:01:54,110 --> 00:01:59,600
Traders can see what these levels are by looking
to past readings and observing the extreme

26
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:05,640
levels the ROC reached before the price reversed.

27
00:02:05,640 --> 00:02:09,380
All markets can work well with the ROC indicator.

28
00:02:09,380 --> 00:02:14,930
There are no right or wrong settings to use,
but every trader has to make decisions depending

29
00:02:14,930 --> 00:02:19,640
on the market conditions and the volatility
of the financial markets.

30
00:02:19,640 --> 00:02:23,090
The ROC indicator can be used on various time
frames.

31
00:02:23,090 --> 00:02:28,349
It can be used for short-term trading but
in general, the value of the ROC indicator

32
00:02:28,349 --> 00:02:32,200
is better used for identifying the long-term
trend.

33
00:02:32,200 --> 00:02:37,760
There are various settings that can be used
for the ROC oscillator.

34
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:42,010
The common settings used for this indicator
is 9-periods.

35
00:02:42,010 --> 00:02:47,040
Other commonly used settings include 14, 21
and even 50.

36
00:02:47,040 --> 00:02:51,560
Remember that there is no absolute number
that can magically give the right settings.

37
00:02:51,560 --> 00:02:56,950
Rather, it is important to analyze the behavior
of the stock or currency you’re trading

38
00:02:56,950 --> 00:03:02,890
in order to use the right or the most appropriate
settings for the price ROC oscillator.

39
00:03:02,890 --> 00:03:08,670
The volatility of the market being analyzed
is of course of utmost importance.

40
00:03:08,670 --> 00:03:14,690
Using too small a number (like 9 for example)
can lead to very choppy readings, while using

41
00:03:14,690 --> 00:03:21,280
a higher configuration setting could potentially
lag the ROC to the point that signals can

42
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:23,590
be very delayed.

43
00:03:23,590 --> 00:03:28,620
If we take a look at this market, you can
see that when using a 5-period setting for

44
00:03:28,620 --> 00:03:32,620
the oscillator, the ROC can be choppy.

45
00:03:32,620 --> 00:03:37,530
While it might look easy in hindsight, it
is important to note that this oscillator

46
00:03:37,530 --> 00:03:43,170
will have problems to pick up the tops and
bottoms or in other words, rising and falling

47
00:03:43,170 --> 00:03:44,860
momentum in price.

48
00:03:44,860 --> 00:03:50,379
So you need to find the right balance suited
for the market you’re trading and the timeframe

49
00:03:50,379 --> 00:03:53,670
you’re mainly using.

50
00:03:53,670 --> 00:04:00,130
How to trade with the price rate of change
First strategy, using the ROC indicator as

51
00:04:00,130 --> 00:04:06,250
a timing tool within a trend analysis
We already know that price never moves in

52
00:04:06,250 --> 00:04:07,560
a straight line.

53
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:11,750
The price posts a series of highs and lows
within the trend.

54
00:04:11,750 --> 00:04:17,000
The challenge is of course in buying near
the low point or the dip in the uptrend or

55
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,700
selling near the high point or the rally in
the downtrend.

56
00:04:20,700 --> 00:04:25,140
The ROC indicator can help you to find these
points.

57
00:04:25,140 --> 00:04:30,500
Trends can be analyzed either by looking at
the highs and lows or by looking at the signals

58
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:34,550
from the technical indicators such as moving
averages.

59
00:04:34,550 --> 00:04:39,790
In this first approach of using the ROC to
analyze a market, let’s look at a simple

60
00:04:39,790 --> 00:04:44,450
set up that involves one moving averages and
the ROC.

61
00:04:44,450 --> 00:04:51,050
Now, maybe the most common way traders use
the ROC oscillator is entering the market

62
00:04:51,050 --> 00:04:54,350
when the plotted line crosses the zero line.

63
00:04:54,350 --> 00:04:59,070
A breakout in either direction indicates increasing
/decreasing momentum.

64
00:04:59,070 --> 00:05:02,600
By itself, this signal is not reliable.

65
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:08,950
Because sometimes, the ROC can dip below the
zero-line only to reverse back higher.

66
00:05:08,950 --> 00:05:11,290
And this is an important point to note.

67
00:05:11,290 --> 00:05:15,680
The ROC reacts to the price and not the other
way around.

68
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:20,760
Therefore, you need to focus on the price
and price action as well before trading this

69
00:05:20,760 --> 00:05:23,790
simple method with the ROC indicator.

70
00:05:23,790 --> 00:05:29,340
We can improve the zero line crossover approach
when we combine the price rate of change with

71
00:05:29,340 --> 00:05:31,980
a trend indicator.

72
00:05:31,980 --> 00:05:37,740
As we can observe in this example, when used
in combination with a moving average the ROC

73
00:05:37,740 --> 00:05:43,090
offers several entries in the market, when
the line crosses below the zero-line.

74
00:05:43,090 --> 00:05:49,610
As most of the oscillators, the rate of change
works well in a trending scenario.

75
00:05:49,610 --> 00:05:53,390
The first step is to determine the prevailing
trend on the market.

76
00:05:53,390 --> 00:05:58,360
You can use the classic moving averages (50,
100 or 200).

77
00:05:58,360 --> 00:06:02,970
In this example I opted for a 50-period simple
moving average

78
00:06:02,970 --> 00:06:07,870
When the price trades above the 50-period
simple moving average, consider taking only

79
00:06:07,870 --> 00:06:09,510
long entries.

80
00:06:09,510 --> 00:06:14,480
And when the price trades below the 50-period
SMA search for short entries

81
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:19,940
Then you monitor the rate of change indicator
and take the zero line crossovers only in

82
00:06:19,940 --> 00:06:23,720
confirmation with the 50-period moving average.

83
00:06:23,720 --> 00:06:28,620
Consider exiting your position when the slope
of the rate of change turns in the opposite

84
00:06:28,620 --> 00:06:30,340
direction.

85
00:06:30,340 --> 00:06:52,220
Here are some examples of zero line crossovers
confirmed by the moving average.

86
00:06:52,220 --> 00:06:57,150
The second strategy involves using the ROC
for divergences

87
00:06:57,150 --> 00:07:02,140
The concept of divergence is the same, whether
you are using the Relative Strength Index

88
00:07:02,140 --> 00:07:05,520
(RSI), the Stochastics or the Price rate of
change.

89
00:07:05,520 --> 00:07:08,820
A divergence is common to all oscillators.

90
00:07:08,820 --> 00:07:14,800
When the oscillator forms a fresh low but
price does not, or when price forms a high

91
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:20,920
but the oscillator does not, it can indicate
a possible divergence and signals a correction.

92
00:07:20,920 --> 00:07:26,340
Using this knowledge, you can apply the price
rate of change and look for divergences with

93
00:07:26,340 --> 00:07:27,340
price.

94
00:07:27,340 --> 00:07:32,960
So a divergence occurs when the price of a
stock or another asset moves in one direction

95
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:37,440
while its ROC moves in the opposite direction.

96
00:07:37,440 --> 00:07:44,300
For example, if a stock's price is rising
over a period of time while the ROC is progressively

97
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:51,050
moving lower, then the ROC is indicating bearish
divergence from price, which signals a possible

98
00:07:51,050 --> 00:07:53,810
trend change to the downside.

99
00:07:53,810 --> 00:08:00,040
The same concept applies if the price is moving
down and ROC is moving higher.

100
00:08:00,040 --> 00:08:03,880
This could signal a price move to the upside.

101
00:08:03,880 --> 00:08:09,810
A divergence is a leading signal but could
prove to be a notoriously poor timing signal

102
00:08:09,810 --> 00:08:15,960
since a divergence can last a long time and
won't always result in a price reversal.

103
00:08:15,960 --> 00:08:20,120
Timing a divergence is maybe even more important
than spotting the pattern.

104
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:24,220
This example shows the ROC indicator posting
a long term divergence.

105
00:08:24,220 --> 00:08:30,520
There are several peaks for the ROC reading,
and all of them would have given wrong trading

106
00:08:30,520 --> 00:08:31,960
signals.

107
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:37,490
One method to time the divergence and filter
the bad signals is to wait for a trend line

108
00:08:37,490 --> 00:08:39,580
breakout on the chart.

109
00:08:39,580 --> 00:08:44,360
Also, you could wait for the price rate of
change to cross below zero level.

110
00:08:44,360 --> 00:08:50,200
In this example, we can see an instance of
divergence that is forming.

111
00:08:50,200 --> 00:08:56,250
Here, price posted a lower low, but the ROC
oscillator posted a higher low.

112
00:08:56,250 --> 00:09:02,180
This divergence, known as bullish divergence
can be used in two ways.

113
00:09:02,180 --> 00:09:08,980
You can go long on the market after this trend
line breakout and after the ROC indicator

114
00:09:08,980 --> 00:09:14,100
crosses above 0, indicating a bullish momentum.

115
00:09:14,100 --> 00:09:19,380
The third approach involves Overbought and
Oversold Conditions

116
00:09:19,380 --> 00:09:24,830
These levels are not fixed, but will vary
depending on the market being traded.

117
00:09:24,830 --> 00:09:30,630
Traders look to see what ROC values resulted
in price reversals in the past.

118
00:09:30,630 --> 00:09:35,700
They try to find both positive and negative
values where the price reversed with some

119
00:09:35,700 --> 00:09:37,880
regularity in the past.

120
00:09:37,880 --> 00:09:43,650
When the ROC reaches these extreme readings
again, they will watch for the price to start

121
00:09:43,650 --> 00:09:46,580
reversing to confirm the ROC signal.

122
00:09:46,580 --> 00:09:51,000
Honestly, I don’t like this approach at
all.

123
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:56,580
This strategy might work in a non-trending
market, but during strong trends traders often

124
00:09:56,580 --> 00:10:01,070
get false signals, as shown in this example.

125
00:10:01,070 --> 00:10:07,250
As I said before, the ROC show readings at
extreme values, but it has no boundaries.

126
00:10:07,250 --> 00:10:14,560
In a very strong uptrend the ROC oscillator
could show readings outside the usual range

127
00:10:14,560 --> 00:10:17,190
within a specific time period.

128
00:10:17,190 --> 00:10:22,810
These overbought or oversold extremes could
be monitored as they could indicate a trend

129
00:10:22,810 --> 00:10:26,350
reversal, but these extreme values are highly
subjective.

130
00:10:26,350 --> 00:10:33,680
So, I wouldn’t concentrate my attention
on overbought or oversold levels.

131
00:10:33,680 --> 00:10:39,990
Another potential problem with using the ROC
indicator is that its calculation gives equal

132
00:10:39,990 --> 00:10:45,450
weight to the most recent price and the price
formed a number of periods ago, despite the

133
00:10:45,450 --> 00:10:52,210
fact that some traders consider more recent
price action to be of more importance in determining

134
00:10:52,210 --> 00:10:54,750
likely future price movements.

135
00:10:54,750 --> 00:10:58,420
This can result in multiple false signals
for trend trades.

136
00:10:58,420 --> 00:11:03,930
That’s why it’s important to keep an eye
on the price action, on recent market swings

137
00:11:03,930 --> 00:11:09,190
and always look at the big picture, on multiple
time frames, to increase you odds of trading

138
00:11:09,190 --> 00:11:11,990
in the right direction.

139
